                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14463590" author="guillaume" created="Mon, 12 Nov 2007 11:38:59 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m not sure I follow in what way it is really a problem, as you don&apos;t use the variables from the binding if your script is empty?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14463530" author="hans_d" created="Mon, 12 Nov 2007 15:35:50 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I have the following use case. For the build dsl I&apos;m developing I have a hierarchical folder structure. Each folder may contain a normal script, or an empty script or an commented out script. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;folder
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;script1&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;childfolder
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;script2&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;childchildfolder
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;script3&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;


&lt;p&gt;The scripts of the subfolder are initialized with the bindings of the parent folders. In the example above this means, even if script2 is empty, it needs to be a container for the bindings of script1, as script3 needs access to all the bindings of the hierarchy. I&apos;m not saying that this is the best solution to the problem, but it is a valid approach. And the groovy behavior described in my attached test case is I think surprising.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I think the principle of least surprise should be the guide here, even though this is not a major use case. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14463576" author="guillaume" created="Mon, 12 Nov 2007 15:43:34 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Have you got a patch to fix that behaviour?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14463579" author="hans_d" created="Tue, 13 Nov 2007 03:57:48 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I have attached a patch.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
